  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Grounding is the practice of constraining Claude's answers to a set of provided source documents and requiring explicit citations for every factual claim. When applied correctly, grounding eliminates most hallucinations at the cost of requiring retrieved context \u2014 making it the single most effective technique for factual accuracy in retrieval-augmented applications."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Grounding and citation pipeline",
          "title": null
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why Grounding Works"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Claude does not retrieve facts from training data when given explicit context in the prompt \u2014 it generates text conditioned on that context. Grounding exploits this property by giving the model all the information it needs to answer and then instructing it to cite the source of each claim. The model can no longer substitute a plausible-sounding but incorrect fact from training data because the constraint is explicit: answer only from what you were given."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Grounding is not a post-processing filter. It is a prompt-level constraint that shifts the model's generation regime. Combined with a strict system prompt and a \"say I don't know\" fallback, it achieves hallucination rates near zero on answerable questions."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Structuring Sources in the Prompt"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "How you format the retrieved documents controls citation accuracy. Number each source block clearly and separate it from surrounding text. A consistent template makes citation straightforward for the model:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def build_grounded_prompt(query: str, docs: list[dict]) -> list[dict]:\n    source_block = \"\"\n    for i, doc in enumerate(docs, 1):\n        source_block += f\"[{i}] Title: {doc['title']}\\n\"\n        source_block += f\"Source: {doc['url']}\\n\"\n        source_block += f\"Content: {doc['text']}\\n\\n\"\n\n    system = (\n        \"You are a research assistant. Answer questions using ONLY the provided sources.\\n\"\n        \"Rules:\\n\"\n        \"1. Cite every factual claim with the source number in brackets, e.g. [1] or [2, 3].\\n\"\n        \"2. If the answer is not in the sources, respond: 'The provided sources do not contain this information.'\\n\"\n        \"3. Never add facts from your own knowledge \u2014 every claim must trace to a source.\\n\"\n        \"4. Quote sparingly; prefer concise paraphrase with citation.\"\n    )\n\n    user = f\"Sources:\\n\\n{source_block}Question: {query}\"\n\n    return [\n        {\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"text\", \"text\": user}]}\n    ], system"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "System Prompt Constraints"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The system prompt is where grounding lives. Weak grounding instructions produce weak results. The minimum effective constraint has three parts:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "A scope restriction: \"Answer ONLY using the provided sources.\" Use capital ONLY \u2014 it signals a hard constraint, not a soft preference."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "A citation requirement: \"After each factual claim, cite the source number in brackets: [1], [2].\" Specify the format explicitly \u2014 models format citations exactly as instructed."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "A fallback instruction: \"If the answer is not in the provided sources, say exactly: 'The provided sources do not contain this information.' Do not guess.\" Without this, the model may synthesize plausible answers when context is insufficient."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Avoid vague formulations such as \"use the context to answer\" or \"base your answer on the provided documents.\" These leave the model room to supplement context with training knowledge."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Citation Formats"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Choose the citation format based on your downstream use case:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Inline numeric [N]:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " best for prose answers. Simple to parse, easy to verify. Default choice."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Footnote list:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " good for longer documents. Citations appear at the end, keeping the main text clean."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Structured JSON:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " best for programmatic consumption. Each statement is a JSON object with text and source_ids fields; allows automated faithfulness checks."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Direct quotation:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " for cases where exact wording matters. Request the model to quote then cite: \\\"... text ...\\\" [1]."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For API integrations that need machine-readable output, the structured JSON format is easiest to validate programmatically:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "STRUCTURED_CITATION_SYSTEM = \"\"\"\nYou are a research assistant. Answer the question using ONLY the provided sources.\nRespond with a JSON object matching this schema:\n{\n  \"answer\": \"your complete answer in prose\",\n  \"statements\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \"a single factual claim\",\n      \"source_ids\": [1, 2]   // list of source numbers supporting this claim\n    }\n  ],\n  \"unanswerable\": false     // true if the sources don't contain the answer\n}\nIf unanswerable is true, set answer to null and statements to [].\nNever fabricate \u2014 every source_id must point to a source that contains the claim.\n\"\"\""
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Extracting and Verifying Citations"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Even a grounded model will occasionally cite the wrong source number or include a paraphrase that drifts from the original. A citation verifier catches these errors before they reach users:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import re\nfrom anthropic import Anthropic\n\nclient = Anthropic()\n\ndef extract_citations(answer: str) -> list[int]:\n    \"\"\"Return sorted unique source numbers cited in the answer.\"\"\"\n    return sorted(set(int(n) for n in re.findall(r'\\[(\\d+)\\]', answer)))\n\ndef verify_citation(\n    claim: str,\n    source_text: str,\n    model: str = \"claude-opus-4-8\"\n) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Ask Claude whether source_text supports the claim.\"\"\"\n    prompt = (\n        f\"Source: {source_text}\\n\\n\"\n        f\"Claim: {claim}\\n\\n\"\n        \"Does the source fully support the claim?\\n\"\n        \"Reply JSON: {\\\"supported\\\": true/false, \\\"reason\\\": \\\"one sentence\\\"}\"\n    )\n    resp = client.messages.create(\n        model=model,\n        max_tokens=128,\n        messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": prompt}]\n    )\n    import json\n    return json.loads(resp.content[0].text)\n\ndef check_answer_citations(\n    answer: str,\n    sources: list[dict]\n) -> list[dict]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Split answer into sentences, extract citations per sentence,\n    verify each cited source supports the sentence.\n    Returns a list of problems found.\n    \"\"\"\n    import re\n    sentences = re.split(r'(?<=[.!?])\\s+', answer)\n    problems = []\n    for sent in sentences:\n        cited = extract_citations(sent)\n        if not cited:\n            # Uncited factual claim \u2014 flag for review\n            if any(c.isupper() for c in sent):\n                problems.append({\"sentence\": sent, \"issue\": \"no_citation\"})\n            continue\n        for idx in cited:\n            if idx < 1 or idx > len(sources):\n                problems.append({\"sentence\": sent, \"issue\": f\"invalid_source_{idx}\"})\n                continue\n            result = verify_citation(sent, sources[idx - 1][\"text\"])\n            if not result[\"supported\"]:\n                problems.append({\n                    \"sentence\": sent,\n                    \"source_id\": idx,\n                    \"issue\": \"unsupported\",\n                    \"reason\": result[\"reason\"]\n                })\n    return problems"
          }
        ]
      },
